Overview

This project simulates a real-world gym membership management system built using Oracle SQL.

It models:

Member lifecycle tracking
Membership status management
Automated status history logging
KPI-driven business reporting

The system demonstrates how relational databases support operational and analytical decision-making in subscription-based businesses.

System Architecture
MEMBERSHIPS
   |
   | status_id
   v
MEMBER_STATUS (lookup table)

MEMBERSHIPS
   |
   | member_id
   v
MEMBER_STATUS_HISTORY (audit log)
Key Features
Database Design
Fully normalized relational schema (3NF principles)
Primary and foreign key constraints
Lookup table for standardized status values
Automation Layer
PL/SQL trigger for automatic status history tracking
Eliminates manual auditing requirements
Analytics Layer
KPI dashboard queries
Revenue estimation
Membership status distribution analysis
Collections monitoring
Scalable Data Model
Supports 15–100+ synthetic member records
Realistic membership lifecycle simulation
Project Structure
schema/        → Tables, constraints, views
data/          → Seed datasets (15 and 100 row versions)
automation/    → Triggers for lifecycle automation
analytics/     → KPI and reporting queries
docs/          → Documentation and ER diagram
Business KPIs

This system supports operational reporting such as:

Total members
Active members
Frozen accounts
Collections rate percentage
Revenue estimates
Membership status distribution
How It Works
Create database schema (tables and constraints)
Load reference data (membership statuses)
Insert member dataset (15 or 100 records)
Enable trigger-based automation
Run KPI and analytics queries
Example KPI Output
Metric	Value
Total Members	100
Active Members	62
Collections Rate	8.5%
Total Revenue	$2,340.00
